SIMPLE: far
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Far
<hw>Far</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Farrow</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A young pig, or a litter
of pigs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Far</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Far
<hw>Far</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<adjf>Farther</adjf> <pr>(#)</pr>
and <adjf>Farthest</adjf> <pr>(#)</pr> are used as the
<pos>compar.</pos> and <pos>superl.</pos> of <ex>far</ex>, although they
are corruptions arising from confusion with <xex>further</xex> and
<xex>furthest</xex>. See <er>Further</er>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fer</ets>, <ets>feor</ets>, AS. <ets>feor</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>fer</ets>, D. <ets>ver</ets>, OHG. <ets>ferro</ets>, adv., G.
<ets>fern</ets>, <pos>a.</pos>, Icel. <ets>fjarri</ets>, Dan.
<ets>fjirn</ets>, Sw. <ets>fjerran</ets>, adv., Goth.
<ets>fa⟦imac⟧rra</ets>, adv., Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/<?/ beyond, Skr.
<ets>paras</ets>, adv., far, and prob. to L. <ets>per</ets> through, and
E. prefix <ets>for-</ets>, as in <ets>for</ets>give, and also to
<ets>fare</ets>. Cf. <er>Farther</er>, <er>Farthest</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Distant in any direction; not near; remote; mutually
separated by a wide space or extent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They said, . . . We be come from a <qex>far</qex> country.</q>
<rj><qau>Josh. ix. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nations <qex>far</qex> and near contend in choice.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Remote from purpose; contrary to design or wishes;
<as>as, <ex>far</ex> be it from me to justify cruelty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Remote in affection or obedience; at a distance,
morally or spiritually; t enmity with; alienated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that are <qex>far</qex> from thee ahsll perish.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lxxiii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Widely different in nature or quality; opposite in
character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was <qex>far</qex> from ill looking, though he thought himself
still farther.</q> <rj><qau>F. Anstey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The more distant of two; <as>as, the <ex>far</ex>
side (called also <ex>off side</ex>) of a horse, that is, the right
side, or the one opposite to the rider when he mounts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The distinction between the adjectival and adverbial use
of <xex>far</xex> is sometimes not easily discriminated.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By far</b></col>, <cd>by much; by a great
difference.</cd> -- <col><b>Far between</b></col>, <cd>with a long
distance (of space or time) between; at long intervals.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The
examinations are few and <xex>far between</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Farrar.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Far</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Far
<hw>Far</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To a great extent or
distance of space; widely; <as>as, we are separated <ex>far</ex> from
each other</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To a great distance in time from any point;
remotely; <as>as, he pushed his researches <ex>far</ex> into
antiquity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In great part; <as>as, the day is <ex>far</ex>
spent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In a great proportion; by many degrees; very much;
deeply; greatly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who can find a virtuous woman ? for her price is <qex>far</qex>
above rubies.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xxxi. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>As far as</b></col>, <cd>to the extent, or degree, that.
See <cref>As far as</cref>, under <er>As</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Far
off</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>At a great distance, absolutely or
relatively.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Distant in sympathy or affection;
alienated.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧But now, in Christ Jesus, ye who some time were
<xex>far off</xex> are made nigh by the blood of Christ.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Eph.
ii. 13.</au> -- <col><b>Far other</b></col>, <cd>different by a great
degree; not the same; quite unlike.</cd> <au>Pope.</au> -- <col><b>Far
and near</b></col>, <cd>at a distance and close by; throughout a whole
region.</cd> -- <col><b>Far and wide</b></col>, <cd>distantly and
broadly; comprehensively.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Far and wide</xex> his eye
commands.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> -- <col><b>From far</b></col>,
<cd>from a great distance; from a remote place.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Far</xex> often occurs in self-explaining
compounds, such as <xex>far</xex>-extended, <xex>far</xex>-reaching,
<xex>far</xex>-spread.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 543 --></p>

<p><ent>Far-about</ent>⟦br⟧
